12:25.445 --> 12:27.847 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what its impact is likely to be.

12:27.880 --> 12:33.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Feinblatt is the president
of Everytown
for Gun Safety, which was
created after the

12:33.186 --> 12:39.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Newtown shootings and supported
in part by
former New York City Mayor
Michael Bloomberg.

12:39.058 --> 12:44.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And David Kopel, he is research
director at
The Independence Institute. It's
a libertarian

12:44.664 --> 12:50.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think tank. And he's well --
also an adjunct
professor of constitutional law
at the University

12:50.269 --> 12:51.738 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Denver.

12:51.771 --> 12:53.606 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we welcome both of you.

12:53.640 --> 12:58.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Feinblatt, is the president
on the right
track with these moves that he
says are going

12:58.578 --> 13:00.313 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to reduce the number of gun
deaths?

13:00.346 --> 13:02.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN FEINBLATT, Everytown for
Gun Safety:
Yes, I think what the president
did today

13:02.248 --> 13:04.350 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was pretty straightforward.

13:04.384 --> 13:10.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What he did was took some
actions to enforce
laws already on the books. One
was, he clarified

13:10.890 --> 13:15.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the law, that, if you're in the
business of
selling guns, you need to get a
license and

13:15.128 --> 13:16.863 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
do a background check.

13:16.896 --> 13:20.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the second is, he said that
he was going
to devote the resources to
enforce it. And

13:21.000 --> 13:26.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that, when you combine
clarifying
the law with additional
enforcement resources,

13:26.673 --> 13:32.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what you're going to do is
interrupt some
commercial sellers who are
actually taking

13:32.178 --> 13:37.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
advantage of loopholes in the
laws, not getting
a license, and selling without
background

13:37.116 --> 13:38.484 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
checks.

13:38.518 --> 13:40.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David Kopel, do
you -- excuse
me for interrupting.

13:40.253 --> 13:42.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
David Kopel, do you agree the
president is
generally on the right track
with this?

13:42.588 --> 13:45.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID KOPEL, The Independence
Institute: Well,
I agree with most of what Mr.
Feinblatt just

13:45.858 --> 13:49.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
said, because the president
didn't do anything
at all that changes the law.

13:50.029 --> 13:56.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He just very forcefully and
passionately restated
what has been the law since
1968, which is,

13:56.402 --> 14:00.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if you are engaged in the
business, as the
statute says, of selling
firearms, then you

14:00.907 --> 14:06.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have to have a federal firearms
license. And
of course he's correct that that
mandate is

14:06.646 --> 14:11.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the same whether you sell in
your basement
or at a gun store or on the
Internet or at

14:11.617 --> 14:13.419 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a gun show.

14:13.453 --> 14:17.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's always been like that.
So, he restated
it. He didn't change anything,
but I think

14:17.990 --> 14:21.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's fine to remind people who
might not know
about that requirement that it
exists.

14:21.761 --> 14:25.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, John
Feinblatt, it's really
not that much of a change? It's
just a matter

14:25.198 --> 14:26.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of enforcing what was already
there?

14:26.999 --> 14:31.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN FEINBLATT: Look, the law
has been blurry.
It's always -- the law has been,
if you're

14:31.037 --> 14:34.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
engaged in the business of
selling guns, you
need to get a license and do
background checks.

14:34.807 --> 14:38.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the problem was that there
was never any
meat on the bone. So, people
didn't know what

14:38.945 --> 14:42.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
engaged in the business actually
meant. And
so what the president did today,
which was

14:43.015 --> 14:49.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very significant, was, he
actually indicated
what would be the criteria to
know whether

14:49.088 --> 14:50.056 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you were engaged in business.

14:50.089 --> 14:51.824 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What are some of
those criteria?

14:51.858 --> 14:56.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN FEINBLATT: So, did you buy
a gun and
recently resell it? And, so,
clearly, you're

14:56.262 --> 15:00.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in it for commerce. It's not
part of your
own collection? It is new in the
box with

15:00.733 --> 15:04.003 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
price tags already on it?

15:04.036 --> 15:08.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are you -- do you have business
cards printed
that actually show that you're
repeatedly

15:08.307 --> 15:14.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
selling guns? Are you showing up
at gun shows
month after month? Things like
that. They're

15:14.480 --> 15:18.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
commonsense, but they are very
important,
because what they're offering is
guidance

15:18.618 --> 15:23.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to both law enforcement and to
people who
are selling guns about who needs
to get a

15:23.356 --> 15:25.158 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
license and who doesn't.

15:25.191 --> 15:31.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then by saying that he would
put enforcement
might behind it, what I think
will happen

15:32.031 --> 15:37.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that you will see dealers
becoming licensed,
doing background checks, where,
heretofore,

15:37.937 --> 15:39.739 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they hadn't.

15:39.772 --> 15:43.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, David Kopel,
just spelling
out some of these specifics
could lead to

15:43.242 --> 15:45.077 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a reduction in gun deaths?

15:45.111 --> 15:48.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID KOPEL: Well, it will lead
to the public
being better informed.

15:48.381 --> 15:54.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I read the guidance document
that the ATF
published today. And it was
fine. It adhered

15:54.353 --> 15:59.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very closely to the statutory
definition enacted
by Congress and then provided
some examples.

15:59.826 --> 16:04.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And part of what it did was
based on court
cases interpreting the statute.

16:04.263 --> 16:10.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that's good. And I think it
will lead
to more people getting federal
firearms licenses,

16:10.069 --> 16:14.207 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is necessary to be engaged
in the business
of selling guns, because what
the president

16:14.240 --> 16:19.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is doing is implicitly reversing
a Clinton
era policy, which was to revoke
dealers' licenses

16:19.946 --> 16:24.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because, supposedly, they
weren't selling
enough guns to count as being
engaged in the

16:24.851 --> 16:26.619 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
business.

16:26.652 --> 16:30.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, 200,000 people lost their
firearms licenses
under the Clinton administration
program,

16:30.923 --> 16:35.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so, hopefully, this is a step to
restore those
licenses that probably never
should have been

16:35.895 --> 16:37.630 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
taken away.

16:37.663 --> 16:39.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David Kopel, what
about some
of the other things the
president is talking

16:39.732 --> 16:46.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about, spending more money on
mental health,
making mental health treatment
more available,

16:46.472 --> 16:51.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
spending money to advance
research to make
guns safer in the hands of
children? What

16:51.711 --> 16:53.679 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about those things? Will those
make a difference?

16:53.713 --> 16:58.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID KOPEL: Oh, the mental
health is really
important, and we, as a country,
tend to only

16:58.251 --> 17:03.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
focus on it when there's these
notorious crimes
committed by a severely mentally
ill person.

17:03.689 --> 17:09.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But just on a day-to-day basis,
one out of
five prisoners in state prisons
for homicide

17:09.362 --> 17:14.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is seriously mentally ill. And,
of course,
people with mental illness are
victimized

17:14.233 --> 17:18.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by violent crime at a much
higher rate than
the general population.

17:18.404 --> 17:23.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I applaud the president for
putting resources
towards that, and that's
something we ought

17:23.643 --> 17:28.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be working on constantly. And
both sides
of the gun debate ought to be
able to come

17:28.281 --> 17:33.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
together to support helping
mentally ill people,
not stigmatizing them, not
having punitive

17:33.552 --> 17:37.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
harsh laws against people, but
just giving
people treatment resources.

17:37.657 --> 17:41.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: John Feinblatt,
given the fact
that, I mean, just at least the
two of you

17:41.460 --> 17:46.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
agree, coming from somewhat
different places
on this, how do you explain the
very vocal

17:46.332 --> 17:47.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
opposition out there?

17:47.500 --> 17:49.235 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

17:49.268 --> 17:50.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN FEINBLATT: Well, it's
interesting, because
it's not just me and David. It's
actually

17:50.303 --> 17:52.204 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
90 percent of Americans.

17:52.238 --> 17:56.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, 90 percent of Americans
believe in universal
background checks. Gun owners
believe in it.

17:56.642 --> 18:02.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even NRA members, 74 percent of
NRA members
do. And so this is what the
American public

18:02.815 --> 18:05.651 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
actually wants. And the
president is taking
steps to do it.

18:05.685 --> 18:11.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, for years, we have
heard these issues
that, if the president acts,
he's going to

18:11.090 --> 18:15.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
take people's guns away, he's
confiscating
guns, it's a slippery slope. And
I think David

18:15.361 --> 18:19.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and I agree that background
checks can save
lives. Americans believe in it.

18:19.765 --> 18:24.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And all the president is really
doing today
is enforcing the laws already on
the books,

18:24.603 --> 18:30.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is what people who oppose
any efforts
at gun safety always say: Why
don't you just

18:30.076 --> 18:31.877 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
enforce the laws on the books?

18:31.911 --> 18:35.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's surprising to hear that
today, when,
in fact, what the president has
done is exactly

18:35.848 --> 18:37.550 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what people have called for.

18:37.583 --> 18:40.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, David Kopel,
though, is
there more the president -- is
there more

18:40.786 --> 18:46.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- what more could -- let me put
it this way.
What more could Congress do to
make it harder

18:47.026 --> 18:50.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for a gun to be in the hands of
someone who
is going to commit a terrible
crime?

18:50.629 --> 18:57.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID KOPEL: Well, I think as
Mr. Feinblatt
said, enforcing existing laws.

18:57.336 --> 19:01.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The -- we have cases where
people have been
straw purchasers. That's
somebody where you're

19:01.907 --> 19:07.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a legal buyer, but you're buying
on behalf
of someone else, so that they
can avoid the

19:07.113 --> 19:12.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
background check and get the
gun. And that's
a very common way that criminals
get guns.

19:12.651 --> 19:15.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the background check system
can't stop
that.

19:15.755 --> 19:21.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the Obama administration's
prosecution
of straw purchase cases has been
very lax,

19:21.694 --> 19:24.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
especially compared to the
previous administration.

19:24.063 --> 19:27.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN FEINBLATT: So, the most
important thing
that you can do is pass
universal background

19:27.833 --> 19:29.035 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
checks.

19:29.068 --> 19:30.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Eighteen states have passed
universal background
checks.

19:30.503 --> 19:31.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Which the U.S.
doesn't have.
We don't have that now.

19:31.937 --> 19:33.706 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN FEINBLATT: Which the U.S.
doesn't have.

19:33.739 --> 19:37.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we're going -- we're moving
state by state.
And in the past year or two, you
have seen

19:37.910 --> 19:43.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Oregon, Colorado, Washington
state, in two
cases by the legislature, in one
case by ballot.

19:43.682 --> 19:49.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you look at the states
that have passed
universal background checks, 48
percent fewer

19:49.155 --> 19:54.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
homicides of cops, 48 percent
fewer domestic
homicides with guns, almost half
the amount

19:54.727 --> 19:56.429 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of trafficking.

19:56.462 --> 19:59.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Background checks work. And it's
important
to know that that's the step
that we have

19:59.932 --> 20:03.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to do. That's the final step
here. It's the
major step.

20:03.302 --> 20:07.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, David Kopel,
that's not
what the president has done so
far. It's not

20:07.506 --> 20:14.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what he's doing today. Would
that make a huge
difference in unnecessary gun
deaths, universal

20:14.847 --> 20:16.682 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
background checks?

20:16.715 --> 20:19.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID KOPEL: Well, we have one
of these Bloomberg
laws that was passed in
Colorado. And I'm

20:19.985 --> 20:24.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
currently representing most of
the state sheriffs
in federal court in a lawsuit
against it because

20:24.623 --> 20:26.459 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it's so badly structured.

20:26.492 --> 20:31.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It makes it very difficult for
people to teach
gun safety classes. For example,
the Washington

20:31.597 --> 20:38.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
analogue, it's illegal if you're
a gun safety
instructor to hand a gun to a
student empty,

20:38.304 --> 20:42.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
unloaded, and show the student
how to handle
it. Those are -- these are
ridiculous laws.

20:42.475 --> 20:44.376 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're not universal background
checks.

20:44.410 --> 20:49.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Colorado law was so badly
structured that
it actually reduced the number
of people getting

20:49.415 --> 20:53.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
background checks because it
made them so
difficult to obtain. So,
whatever polls say

20:53.686 --> 20:59.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about the theory of background
checks, the
practice and the laws pushed by
Everytown

20:59.425 --> 21:05.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has been terrible and highly
destructive to
the shooting sports and
responsible gun use.

21:05.131 --> 21:08.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just quickly, so
it sounds
like, once one gets beyond what
the president

21:08.901 --> 21:10.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
suggested today, you do see
opposition?

21:10.736 --> 21:14.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN FEINBLATT: You see it, but
you see it
-- certainly, David objects it
to, but every

21:15.007 --> 21:18.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
poll would show that 90 percent
of Americans
believe in universal background
checks, whether

21:18.777 --> 21:22.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you're a gun owner, whether
you're not a gun
owner, whether you live in a
rural community

21:22.548 --> 21:24.483 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or an urban community.

21:24.517 --> 21:28.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's what the American public
wants. It's
what the people of Washington
state voted

21:28.154 --> 21:32.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for on their own at the ballot,
and it's what
state legislatures are passing.

21:32.091 --> 21:36.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, and, today,
we're looking
at what the president did
through his executive

21:36.629 --> 21:37.363 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
actions.

21:37.396 --> 21:38.697 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN FEINBLATT: That's correct.

21:38.731 --> 21:40.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: John Feinblatt,
David Kopel,
we thank you both.

21:40.900 --> 21:46.038 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID KOPEL: Thank you.

21:46.071 --> 21:51.177 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN FEINBLATT: Thank you.

